<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-Change-of-Variables">
    <title>4.6 Change of Variables and Jacobians</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this section, we will explore the technique of changing variables in multiple integrals. 
            This method allows us to simplify the evaluation of integrals by transforming the region of 
            integration into a more convenient shape.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <p>
  In one-dimensional calculus, we often use a change of variables (a substitution) to simplify an integral as:
  <me>\int^b_a f(x)\,dx = \int^d_c f(g(u))g'(u)\,du,</me>
  where <m>x=g(u)</m>, <m>a=g(c)</m>, and <m>b=g(d)</m>. We consider a change of variables that is given by a <term>transformation</term> <m>T</m> from the <m>uv</m>-plane to the <m>xy</m>-plane:
  <me>T(u,v) = (x,y),</me>
  where <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are related to <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> by the equations:
  <me>x=g(u,v), \quad y=h(u,v).</me>
  A transformation <m>T</m> is a function whose domain and range are both subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. 
  If <m>T(u_1,v_1)=(x_1,y_1)</m>, then the point <m>(x_1,y_1)</m> is called the <term>image</term> of the point <m>(u_1,v_1)</m>. 
  If no two points share the same image, <m>T</m> is called <term>one-to-one</term>. 
  If <m>T</m> is a one-to-one transformation, then it has an <term>inverse transformation</term> <m>T^{-1}</m> from the <m>xy</m>-plane to the <m>uv</m>-plane, making it possible to solve the equations for <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> in terms of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>:
  <me>u=G(x,y), \quad v=H(x,y).</me>
   </p>

<!-- Side-by-Side Figure Panel Configuration -->
<sidebyside widths="45% 38%" valigns="middle middle">
  
  <!-- Left Panel: uv-Plane Region S -->
  <figure xml:id="fig-transformation-uv-plane">
    <caption>The original region <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane.</caption>
    <image xml:id="img-transformation-uv-plane">
      <description>A 2D coordinate plot of the uv-plane containing a shaded rectangular domain S, with a mapping arrow pointing towards the right side of the page.</description>
      <latex-image>
        <![CDATA[
        \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.8cm, y=1.8cm, >=latex]
          % Shaded Region S (A simple rectangular block domain)
          \fill[blue!15] (0.4, 0.3) rectangle (1.4, 1.1);
          
          % Primary Axes Space
          \draw[->, thick] (-0.2, 0) -- (1.8, 0) node[below] {$u$};
          \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.2) -- (0, 1.5) node[left] {$v$};
          
          % Bounding Path Box
          \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (0.4, 0.3) rectangle (1.4, 1.1);
          
          % Metadata Text and Domain Labels
          \node at (0.9, 0.7) {\small Region $S$};
          
          % Transformation Curving Arrow Mapping Vector Indicator
          \draw[->, thick, cyan!80!black, bend left=15] (1.6, 1.0) to node[above, black] {$T$} (2.3, 0.9);
        \end{tikzpicture}
        ]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <!-- Right Panel: xy-Plane Region R -->
  <figure xml:id="fig-transformation-xy-plane">
    <caption>The transformed image region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane.</caption>
    <image xml:id="img-transformation-xy-plane">
      <description>A 2D coordinate plot of the xy-plane containing an irregularly curved shaded shape region R, serving as the image map of S.</description>
      <latex-image>
        <![CDATA[
        \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.8cm, y=1.8cm, >=latex]
          % Shaded Image Region R (Curved using safe Bézier control anchors)
          \fill[blue!15] (0.4, 0.5) .. controls (0.6, 1.3) and (1.2, 1.1) .. (1.5, 0.8)
                                    .. controls (1.3, 0.3) and (0.8, 0.2) .. (0.4, 0.5);
          
          % Primary Axes Space
          \draw[->, thick] (-0.2, 0) -- (1.8, 0) node[below] {$x$};
          \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.2) -- (0, 1.5) node[left] {$y$};
          
          % Boundary Contour Path Line
          \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (0.4, 0.5) .. controls (0.6, 1.3) and (1.2, 1.1) .. (1.5, 0.8)
                                                 .. controls (1.3, 0.3) and (0.8, 0.2) .. (0.4, 0.5);
          
          % Metadata Region Label
          \node at (0.9, 0.65) {\small Region $R = T(S)$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
        ]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

</sidebyside>

<example xml:id="ex-transformation-parabolic">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A transformation <m>T</m> is defined by the equations:
      <me>x = u^2 - v^2, \quad y = 2uv.</me>
      Find the image of the square region <m>S = \{(u,v): 0 \leq u \leq 1, \ 0 \leq v \leq 1\}</m> under this transformation.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Map the Four Boundaries of the Square <m>S</m></strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      To find the image region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane, we map the four boundary edges of the square <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane one by one:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Boundary <m>S_1</m> (Bottom Edge):</strong> Along this line, <m>v = 0</m> while <m>u</m> runs from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>. Substituting <m>v = 0</m> into our transformation equations gives:
          <me>x = u^2, \quad y = 0.</me>
          As <m>u</m> ranges from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>, <m>x</m> moves from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>. This maps to a straight line segment along the positive <m>x</m>-axis from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(1,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Boundary <m>S_2</m> (Right Edge):</strong> Along this line, <m>u = 1</m> while <m>v</m> runs from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>. Substituting <m>u = 1</m> yields:
          <me>x = 1 - v^2, \quad y = 2v.</me>
          We can eliminate the parameter <m>v</m> by isolating it from the second equation: <m>v = \frac{y}{2}</m>. Substituting this into the first equation describes a parabola in the <m>xy</m>-plane:
          <me>x = 1 - \left(\frac{y}{2}\right)^2 \implies x = 1 - \frac{1}{4}y^2.</me>
          As <m>v</m> moves from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>, <m>y</m> sweeps from <m>0</m> to <m>2</m>, mapping this boundary to a parabolic arc running from <m>(1,0)</m> up to <m>(0,2)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Boundary <m>S_3</m> (Top Edge):</strong> Along this line, <m>v = 1</m> while <m>u</m> runs from <m>1</m> down to <m>0</m>. Substituting <m>v = 1</m> gives:
          <me>x = u^2 - 1, \quad y = 2u \implies u = \frac{y}{2}.</me>
          Substituting <m>u</m> back into the expression for <m>x</m> describes another parabola:
          <me>x = \left(\frac{y}{2}\right)^2 - 1 \implies x = \frac{1}{4}y^2 - 1.</me>
          As <m>u</m> moves from <m>1</m> down to <m>0</m>, <m>y</m> tracks from <m>2</m> down to <m>0</m>, mapping this boundary to a parabolic arc from <m>(0,2)</m> back left to <m>(-1,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Boundary <m>S_4</m> (Left Edge):</strong> Along this line, <m>u = 0</m> while <m>v</m> tracks from <m>1</m> down to <m>0</m>. Substituting <m>u = 0</m> gives:
          <me>x = -v^2, \quad y = 0.</me>
          As <m>v</m> ranges from <m>1</m> down to <m>0</m>, <m>x</m> moves from <m>-1</m> back to <m>0</m>. This maps directly to a straight line segment along the negative <m>x</m>-axis from <m>(-1,0)</m> returning to the origin <m>(0,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Side-by-Side Figure Panel Grid Mapping -->
    <sidebyside widths="45% 48%" valigns="middle middle">
      
      <!-- Left Panel: Domain S in uv-plane -->
      <figure xml:id="fig-square-uv-domain">
        <caption>The square domain region <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-square-uv-domain">
          <description>A 2D coordinate plot mapping a shaded unit square region from 0 to 1 along both the u and v axes.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=2.5cm, y=2.5cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Square S
              \fill[blue!15] (0,0) rectangle (1,1);
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric layout)
              \draw[->, thick] (-0.2, 0) -- (1.4, 0) node[below] {$u$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.2) -- (0, 1.4) node[left] {$v$};
              
              % Outer Parameter Edges
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (0,0) rectangle (1,1);
              
              % Text Labels
              \node at (0.5, 0.5) {\small Region $S$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,0)$};
              \fill (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$1$};
              \fill (0,1) circle (1.5pt) node[left] {$1$};
              \fill (1,1) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$(1,1)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <!-- Right Panel: Transformed Image R in xy-plane -->
      <figure xml:id="fig-parabolic-xy-image">
        <caption>The transformed image region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-parabolic-xy-image">
          <description>A 2D coordinate plot mapping an upper lens-shaped parabolic region bounded below by the x axis from negative 1 to positive 1 and capped above by intersecting parabolas peaking at y=2.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.25cm, y=1.25cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Image Region R bounded below by y=0 and above by the parabolas
              \fill[blue!15] plot[domain=0:2, samples=30, variable=\y] ({1-0.25*\y*\y}, \y) -- 
                            plot[domain=2:0, samples=30, variable=\y] ({0.25*\y*\y-1}, \y) -- cycle;
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric layout)
              \draw[->, thick] (-1.5, 0) -- (1.5, 0) node[below] {$x$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.4) -- (0, 2.5) node[left] {$y$};
              
              % Parabolic Boundary Outline Curves
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick, domain=0:2, samples=40, variable=\y] plot ({1-0.25*\y*\y}, \y);
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick, domain=0:2, samples=40, variable=\y] plot ({0.25*\y*\y-1}, \y);
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (-1,0) -- (1,0);
              
              % Variable Text Labels
              \node at (0, 0.75) {\small Region $R$};
              \node[above right, blue!60!black] at (0.4, 1.4) {\small $x=1-\frac{1}{4}y^2$};
              \node[above left, blue!60!black] at (-0.4, 1.4) {\small $x=\frac{1}{4}y^2-1$};
              
              % Intercept Coordinate Vertices
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,0)$};
              \fill (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$(1,0)$};
              \fill (-1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(-1,0)$};
              \fill (0,2) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$(0,2)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Conclusion</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The image of the square region <m>S</m> is the upper lens-shaped region <m>R</m> in the upper half-plane of the <m>xy</m>-space bounded below by the interval <m>[-1, 1]</m> along the <m>x</m>-axis and capped above by the two meeting parabolas intersecting at <m>(0,2)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-polar-coordinate-curves-mapping">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>P(x,y)</m> is any point with <m>x \neq 0</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane, let:
      <me>r = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}, \quad \theta = \arctan\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)</me>
      and let <m>P(0,b)</m> correspond to <m>r=b, \ \theta =\pi/2</m>. Sketch in the <m>r\theta</m>-plane, the graphs of <m>r=1, \ r=2, \ r=3</m> and <m>\theta=-1/2, \ \theta =1/2</m>. Sketch the corresponding <m>r</m>-curves and <m>\theta</m>-curves in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Analysis and Interpretation:</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      This problem demonstrates how grid curves translate between a polar parameter coordinate space (<m>r\theta</m>-plane) and physical space (<m>xy</m>-plane):
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          In the <m>r\theta</m>-plane, constant-radius curves (<m>r=c</m>) are simple vertical lines, and constant-angle curves (<m>\theta=c</m>) are simple horizontal lines. Together, they form a orthogonal rectangular grid network.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In the <m>xy</m>-plane, constant-radius curves (<m>r=c</m>) transform into concentric circles centered at the origin with a radius of <m>c</m>. Constant-angle curves (<m>\theta=c</m>) transform into straight radial rays shooting outward from the origin at a baseline heading angle of <m>c</m> radians (where <m>\pm 1/2 \text{ rad} \approx \pm 28.6^\circ</m>).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Side-by-Side Coordinate Space Transformation Grid -->
    <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" valigns="middle middle">
      
      % Left Panel: Orthogonal rectangular net inside the parameter space (r-theta plane)
      <figure xml:id="fig-polar-parameter-r-theta-plane">
        <caption>Constant grid lines plotted inside the <m>r\theta</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-polar-parameter-r-theta-plane">
          <description>A 2D plot of the r-theta plane showing vertical grid lines at r=1, 2, 3 and horizontal lines at theta= -0.5 and 0.5.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.2cm, y=1.5cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Region bounded by the parameter envelopes
              \fill[blue!10] (1.0, -0.5) rectangle (3.0, 0.5);
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric balanced 1:1 setup)
              \draw[->, thick] (-0.3, 0) -- (3.5, 0) node[below] {$r$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.8) -- (0, 1.0) node[left] {$\theta$};
              
              % Constant r-curves (Vertical lines)
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (1, -0.7) -- (1, 0.9) node[above] {\small $r=1$};
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (2, -0.7) -- (2, 0.9) node[above] {\small $r=2$};
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (3, -0.7) -- (3, 0.9) node[above] {\small $r=3$};
              
              % Constant theta-curves (Horizontal lines)
              \draw[red!80!black, thick] (-0.2, 0.5) -- (3.3, 0.5) node[right] {\small $\theta=\frac{1}{2}$};
              \draw[red!80!black, thick] (-0.2, -0.5) -- (3.3, -0.5) node[right] {\small $\theta=-\frac{1}{2}$};
              
              % Axis intercept ticks
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$0$};
              \node[below left] at (0, 0.5) {\small $1/2$};
              \node[below left] at (0, -0.5) {\small $-1/2$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      % Right Panel: Concentric circles and angular rays inside physical space (xy-plane)
      <figure xml:id="fig-polar-transformed-xy-plane">
        <caption>The corresponding <m>r</m>-curves and <m>\theta</m>-curves inside the <m>xy</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-polar-transformed-xy-plane">
          <description>A 2D plot of the xy-plane showing concentric circles of radius 1, 2, 3 and two radial rays emerging from the origin at angles of 28.6 degrees above and below the x axis.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.0cm, y=1.0cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Sector Area corresponding to the parameter space region S
              % 1/2 radians is approx 28.65 degrees. We fill the sector segment from -28.65 to 28.65 degrees between r=1 and r=3.
              \fill[blue!10, domain=-28.65:28.65, samples=40, variable=\t] 
                plot ({1*cos(\t)}, {1*sin(\t)}) -- plot ({3*cos(28.65-\t-28.65)}, {3*sin(28.65-\t-28.65)}) -- cycle;
              
              % Primary Cartesian Axes System (Isometric 1:1 isometric ratio constraints)
              \draw[->, thick] (-3.4, 0) -- (3.6, 0) node[below] {$x$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -1.8) -- (0, 1.8) node[left] {$y$};
              
              % Constant r-curves: Concentric Full Reference Circle Tracks (Drawn via safe explicit paths)
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick, domain=0:360, samples=80, variable=\t] plot ({1*cos(\t)}, {1*sin(\t)});
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick, domain=0:360, samples=80, variable=\t] plot ({2*cos(\t)}, {2*sin(\t)});
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick, domain=0:360, samples=80, variable=\t] plot ({3*cos(\t)}, {3*sin(\t)});
              
              % Constant theta-curves: Radial Ray Tracking Vectors shooting out into the plane quadrants
              % Ray 1: theta = 1/2 rad (approx 28.65 degrees)
              \draw[red!80!black, thick, ->] (0,0) -- (28.65:3.5) node[above right] {\small $\theta=\frac{1}{2}$};
              % Ray 2: theta = -1/2 rad (approx -28.65 degrees)
              \draw[red!80!black, thick, ->] (0,0) -- (-28.65:3.5) node[below right] {\small $\theta=-\frac{1}{2}$};
              
              % Structural Annotation Labels
              \node[blue!60!black, below left] at (-1.0, 0) {\small $r=1$};
              \node[blue!60!black, below left] at (-2.0, 0) {\small $r=2$};
              \node[blue!60!black, below left] at (-3.0, 0) {\small $r=3$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$(0,0)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
  </solution>
</example>

<definition xml:id="def-jacobian-2d">
  <title>The Jacobian Determinant</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>x=f(u,v)</m> and <m>y=g(u,v)</m>, then the <term>Jacobian</term> of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with respect to <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>, denoted by <m>\displaystyle \frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial (u,v)}</m>, is:
      <me>\frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial (u,v)} = \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial x}{\partial u} \amp \frac{\partial x}{\partial v} \\ \frac{\partial y}{\partial u} \amp \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} \end{vmatrix} = \frac{\partial x}{\partial u}\frac{\partial y}{\partial v} - \frac{\partial y}{\partial u}\frac{\partial x}{\partial v}.</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<theorem xml:id="thm-change-of-variables-double">
  <title>Change of Variables in a Double Integral</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>x=f(u,v)</m> and <m>y=g(u,v)</m> is a transformation of coordinates, and if the Jacobian <m>\displaystyle \frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial (u,v)}</m> does not change sign in <m>S</m>, then:
      <me>\iint_R F(x,y)\,dA = \iint_S F(f(u,v), g(u,v)) \left| \frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial (u,v)} \right| \,dudv.</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<example xml:id="ex-transformation-jacobian-evaluation">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Evaluate the double integral:
      <me>\int^4_0 \int^{x=(y/2)+1}_{x=y/2} \frac{2x-y}{2} \, dxdy</me>
      by applying the transformation:
      <me>u = \frac{2x-y}{2}, \quad v = \frac{y}{2}</me>
      and integrating over the corresponding region in the <m>uv</m>-plane.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Find the Inverse Transformation and the Jacobian</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      To transition the integral into the new coordinate system, we solve the transformation equations for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in terms of <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>:
      <me>v = \frac{y}{2} \implies y = 2v</me>
      Substituting this into the first equation:
      <me>u = \frac{2x - 2v}{2} \implies u = x - v \implies x = u + v</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Next, we calculate the Jacobian determinant <m>J(u,v)</m> of this transformation:
      <me>\frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial(u,v)} = \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial x}{\partial u} \amp \frac{\partial x}{\partial v} \\ \frac{\partial y}{\partial u} \amp \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} \end{vmatrix} = \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \end{vmatrix} = (1)(2) - (1)(0) = 2</me>
      The area differential element transforms as: <m>dxdy = \left| \frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial(u,v)} \right| \, dudv = 2 \, dudv</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Map the Region of Integration</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The boundaries of the original region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane are given by the limits of the iterated integral:
      <me>y = 0, \quad y = 4, \quad x = \frac{y}{2}, \quad x = \frac{y}{2} + 1</me>
      We translate these boundary walls into the <m>uv</m>-plane using our substitutions:
      <ul>
        <li><p>The lower edge <m>y = 0 \implies 2v = 0 \implies v = 0</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The upper edge <m>y = 4 \implies 2v = 4 \implies v = 2</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The left edge <m>x = \frac{y}{2} \implies u + v = v \implies u = 0</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The right edge <m>x = \frac{y}{2} + 1 \implies u + v = v + 1 \implies u = 1</m>.</p></li>
      </ul>
      This shows that the original skewed parallelogram region <m>R</m> maps to a simple rectangular domain <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane: <m>S = \{(u,v) : 0 \leq u \leq 1, \ 0 \leq v \leq 2\}</m>.
    </p>

    <!-- Side-by-Side Spatial Mapping Panel Grid -->
    <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" valigns="middle middle">
      
      <!-- Left Panel: Original Parallelogram Region R in xy-plane -->
      <figure xml:id="fig-parallelogram-xy-region">
        <caption>The original region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-parallelogram-xy-region">
          <description>A 2D coordinate plot mapping a slanted parallelogram starting at the origin and shifting right as y climbs up to 4.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.5cm, y=1.0cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Parallelogram R
              \fill[blue!15] (0,0) -- (1,0) -- (3,4) -- (2,4) -- cycle;
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric 1:1 scale layout)
              \draw[->, thick] (-0.5, 0) -- (3.5, 0) node[below] {$x$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.5) -- (0, 4.5) node[left] {$y$};
              
              % Boundary Outline Tracks
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (0,0) -- (1,0) -- (3,4) -- (2,4) -- cycle;
              \draw[dashed, gray] (0,4) -- (2,4);
              
              % Labels and Intercept Points
              \node at (1.5, 2.0) {\small Region $R$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,0)$};
              \fill (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$(1,0)$};
              \fill (2,4) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$(2,4)$};
              \fill (3,4) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$(3,4)$};
              \node[left] at (0,4) {\small $4$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <!-- Right Panel: Transformed Rectangle Region S in uv-plane -->
      <figure xml:id="fig-rectangular-uv-region">
        <caption>The transformed rectangular region <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-rectangular-uv-region">
          <description>A 2D coordinate plot mapping a simple unit rectangle spanning from u=0 to 1 and v=0 to 2.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=2.5cm, y=1.25cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Rectangle S
              \fill[blue!15] (0,0) rectangle (1,2);
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric 1:1 scale layout)
              \draw[->, thick] (-0.2, 0) -- (1.4, 0) node[below] {$u$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.2) -- (0, 2.4) node[left] {$v$};
              
              % Boundary Outline Edges
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (0,0) rectangle (1,2);
              
              % Labels and Key Intercept Coordinates
              \node at (0.5, 1.0) {\small Region $S$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,0)$};
              \fill (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$1$};
              \fill (0,2) circle (1.5pt) node[left] {$2$};
              \fill (1,2) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$(1,2)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      <strong>Step 3: Setup and Evaluate the Transformed Integral</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Substituting the new tracking variables, the integrand <m>\frac{2x-y}{2} = u</m>, the Jacobian factor, and our bounds into the theorem equation, we get:
      <me>\iint_R \left(\frac{2x-y}{2}\right)\,dxdy = \int_{0}^{2} \int_{0}^{1} u \cdot \Big( 2 \, dudv \Big)</me>
      Since the constant bounds let us decouple the double integration into a simple single product setup:
      <md>
        <mrow>= 2 \left( \int_{0}^{2} \, dv \right) \left( \int_{0}^{1} u \, du \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>= 2 \cdot \Big[ v \Big]_{0}^{2} \cdot \left[ \frac{1}{2}u^2 \right]_{0}^{1}</mrow>
        <mrow>= 2 \cdot (2 - 0) \cdot \left( \frac{1}{2}(1)^2 - 0 \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>= 2 \cdot 2 \cdot \frac{1}{2} = 2.</mrow>
      </md>
      The value of the double integral calculated via change of variables is exactly <m>2</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-jacobian-trapezoid-exp">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Evaluate the double integral:
      <me>\iint_R e^{(y-x)/(y+x)} \,dxdy,</me>
      where <m>R</m> is the region in the <m>xy</m>-plane bounded by the trapezoid with vertices <m>(0,1)</m>, <m>(0,2)</m>, <m>(2,0)</m>, and <m>(1,0)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Choose a Transformation and Find its Inverse</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Looking at the structure of the integrand and the boundary behaviors of the trapezoid, we can simplify the problem by defining the new tracking variables:
      <me>u = y - x \quad \text{and} \quad v = y + x.</me>
      We solve this system of linear equations for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in terms of <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> to find the inverse transformation equations:
      <me>v + u = (y + x) + (y - x) = 2y \implies y = \frac{1}{2}(v + u)</me>
      <me>v - u = (y + x) - (y - x) = 2x \implies x = \frac{1}{2}(v - u)</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Calculate the Jacobian Matrix Determinant</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Using <xref ref="def-jacobian-2d" />, we compute the partial derivative array:
      <me>\frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial (u,v)} = \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial x}{\partial u} \amp \frac{\partial x}{\partial v} \\ \frac{\partial y}{\partial u} \amp \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} \end{vmatrix} = \begin{vmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{vmatrix} = \left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) - \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) = -\frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{4} = -\frac{1}{2}.</me>
      Taking the absolute value, the area differential element transforms as: <m>dxdy = \left| -\frac{1}{2} \right| \,dudv = \frac{1}{2}\,dudv</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 3: Map the Integration Regions</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The trapezoidal region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane is bounded by four line segments: the <m>y</m>-axis (<m>x=0</m>), the <m>x</m>-axis (<m>y=0</m>), and the slanted parallel lines connecting the intercepts, which are <m>x+y=1</m> and <m>x+y=2</m>. 
      Substituting our definitions for <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>, we find their values along these boundaries:
      <ul>
        <li><p>Along the boundary line <m>x+y=1 \implies v = 1</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Along the boundary line <m>x+y=2 \implies v = 2</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Along the <m>y</m>-axis line <m>x=0 \implies \frac{1}{2}(v-u) = 0 \implies u = v</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Along the <m>x</m>-axis line <m>y=0 \implies \frac{1}{2}(v+u) = 0 \implies u = -v</m>.</p></li>
      </ul>
      This transforms the skewed trapezoid <m>R</m> into a simpler trapezoidal region <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane bounded by the horizontal lines <m>v=1, v=2</m> and the rays <m>u=-v, u=v</m>.
    </p>

    <!-- Side-by-Side Coordinate Space Transformation Grid -->
    <sidebyside widths="45% 50%" valigns="middle middle">
      
      <!-- Left Panel: Original Trapezoid R in the xy-plane -->
      <figure xml:id="fig-trapezoid-xy-region">
        <caption>The original trapezoidal region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-trapezoid-xy-region">
          <description>A 2D coordinate plot mapping a shaded trapezoid in the first quadrant 
            bounded by the axes and parallel slanted lines running between x+y=1 and x+y=2.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.6cm, y=1.6cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Trapezoid R
              \fill[blue!15] (1,0) -- (2,0) -- (0,2) -- (0,1) -- cycle;
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric 1:1 scale layout)
              \draw[->, thick] (-0.3, 0) -- (2.5, 0) node[below] {$x$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.3) -- (0, 2.5) node[left] {$y$};
              
              % Boundary Outline Tracks
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (1,0) -- (2,0) -- (0,2) -- (0,1) -- cycle;
              
              % Labels and Intercept Points
              \node at (0.6, 0.6) {\small Region $R$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,0)$};
              \fill (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$1$};
              \fill (2,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$2$};
              \fill (0,1) circle (1.5pt) node[left] {$1$};
              \fill (0,2) circle (1.5pt) node[left] {$2$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <!-- Right Panel: Transformed Region S in the uv-plane -->
      <figure xml:id="fig-trapezoid-uv-region">
        <caption>The transformed region <m>S</m> in the <m>uv</m>-plane.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-trapezoid-uv-region">
          <description>A 2D coordinate plot mapping an upside-down trapezoid centered on the vertical v-axis, opening outward as v goes from 1 to 2.</description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.0cm, y=1.2cm, >=latex]
              % Shaded Region S
              \fill[blue!15] (-1,1) -- (1,1) -- (2,2) -- (-2,2) -- cycle;
              
              % Coordinate Axes (Isometric balanced 1:1 layout)
              \draw[->, thick] (-2.5, 0) -- (2.5, 0) node[below] {$u$};
              \draw[->, thick] (0, -0.3) -- (0, 2.5) node[left] {$v$};
              
              % Boundary Outline Edges
              \draw[blue!80!black, thick] (-1,1) -- (1,1) -- (2,2) -- (-2,2) -- cycle;
              \draw[gray, dashed] (-2,1) -- (2,1);
              \draw[gray, dashed] (-2,2) -- (2,2);
              
              % Functional Bound Guideline Ray Tracks
              \draw[blue!60!black, thin, domain=0:2] plot ({\x}, {\x}) node[right] {\small $u=v$};
              \draw[blue!60!black, thin, domain=0:2] plot ({-\x}, {\x}) node[left] {\small $u=-v$};
              
              % Labels and Key Intercept Coordinates
              \node at (0, 1.5) {\small Region $S$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$0$};
              \node[left] at (0,1) {\small $1$};
              \node[left] at (0,2) {\small $2$};
              \fill (1,1) circle (1.2pt) node[below right] {\small $(1,1)$};
              \fill (2,2) circle (1.2pt) node[above right] {\small $(2,2)$};
              \fill (-1,1) circle (1.2pt) node[below left] {\small $(-1,1)$};
              \fill (-2,2) circle (1.2pt) node[above left] {\small $(-2,2)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      <strong>Step 4: Set Up and Evaluate the Transformed Integral</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      We rewrite the iterated double integral using our new boundaries, substituting the integrand <m>\frac{y-x}{y+x} = \frac{u}{v}</m> and the area differential element <m>dxdy = \frac{1}{2}\,dudv</m>:
      <me>\iint_R e^{\frac{y-x}{y+x}} \,dxdy = \int_{1}^{2} \int_{-v}^{v} e^{u/v} \cdot \left( \frac{1}{2} \, dudv \right)</me>
      First, we integrate the inner expression with respect to <m>u</m>, treating <m>v</m> as a constant factor:
      <md>
        <mrow>\int_{-v}^{v} \frac{1}{2} e^{u/v} \, du \amp = \left[ \frac{1}{2} \cdot v e^{u/v} \right]_{u=-v}^{u=v}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}v \left( e^{v/v} - e^{-v/v} \right) = \frac{1}{2}v \left( e^1 - e^{-1} \right).</mrow>
      </md>
      Next, we substitute this result into the outer structural layer and integrate with respect to <m>v</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>\int_{1}^{2} \frac{1}{2}v (e - e^{-1}) \, dv \amp = \frac{1}{2}(e - e^{-1}) \int_{1}^{2} v \, dv</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}(e - e^{-1}) \left[ \frac{1}{2}v^2 \right]_{1}^{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{4}(e - e^{-1}) \Big( (2)^2 - (1)^2 \Big)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{4}(e - e^{-1})(4 - 1) = \frac{3}{4}(e - e^{-1}).</mrow>
      </md>
      The exact value of the double integral over the trapezoidal region is <m>\frac{3}{4}(e - e^{-1})</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

</section>